### 1. One-Line Summary
* Rakza 7 is the firmer, more stable, and more direct all-round offensive rubber, while Rakza 7 Soft keeps the same family identity but adds more dwell, easier access to spin, and a softer, more forgiving feel.

### 2. Head-to-Head Breakdown
* **Speed & Gears:**
    * **Low Impact:** Rakza 7 Soft feels livelier and easier to activate on light brush shots, soft counters, and compact topspins. Rakza 7 feels slightly more restrained at low impact, but also more solid and less jumpy.
    * **Top End:** Rakza 7 has the higher ceiling when you swing hard. Its firmer sponge transfers power more cleanly on full strokes, especially from mid distance.
    * **Linearity:** Rakza 7 is more linear and predictable across impact levels. Rakza 7 Soft has a bit more catapult sensation, so the jump from soft touch to engaged impact is more noticeable.

* **Spin Mechanics:**
    * **Opening Loop:** Rakza 7 Soft is easier for opening against backspin because the softer sponge lets the ball sink in more easily and helps lift the ball with less physical effort.
    * **Max Spin:** Rakza 7 usually produces the heavier spin at high-quality contact because the firmer base holds up better under stronger acceleration.
    * **Topsheet Grip:** Both have strong grip and a very similar topsheet character, but Rakza 7 Soft feels grippier in use for many players because the softer sponge increases dwell and makes brush contact easier to feel.

* **Flight Path (Throw Angle):**
    * **Arc Height:** Rakza 7 Soft throws a little higher and gives a rounder arc. Rakza 7 is slightly flatter and more direct.
    * **Safety:** Rakza 7 Soft offers more net clearance and is easier when you are under pressure or slightly late. Rakza 7 gives good safety too, but it rewards better timing more.

* **Feel & Feedback:**
    * **Sensation:** Rakza 7 feels firmer, crisper, and more compact at contact. Rakza 7 Soft feels softer, cushier, and more elastic.
    * **Dwell:** Rakza 7 Soft clearly has more dwell time. Rakza 7 releases the ball faster and feels more immediate.

* **Control & Short Game:**
    * **Sensitivity:** Rakza 7 is a bit less sensitive to incoming spin and easier to keep tight on pushes and service return when your touch is firm. Rakza 7 Soft is more reactive, especially if your hand is passive.
    * **Touch Play:** Rakza 7 Soft gives a very pleasant touch for flick initiation, slow spinny openings, and controlled placements. Rakza 7 is better for firmer, cleaner short-game technique and keeping the ball low without extra bounce.

* **Blocking & Countering:**
    * **Passive Block:** Rakza 7 is more stable on passive blocks, especially against stronger topspin. The firmer sponge resists bottoming out better.
    * **Active Counter:** Rakza 7 Soft is easier for compact counter-topspin close to the table, but Rakza 7 is stronger when the pace rises and the contact gets more forceful.

### 3. The Recommendation
* **Choose Rakza 7 if:**
    * You want the more balanced and complete offensive option.
    * You value stability, directness, and better high-end power.
    * You block a lot, counter firmly, or hit through the ball more often.
    * You prefer a crisper, firmer contact and more linear response.

* **Choose Rakza 7 Soft if:**
    * You want easier spin access, higher arc, and more dwell.
    * You prioritize comfort, forgiveness, and easier opening loops.
    * You play close to the table with more brushing, rolling, and controlled topspin exchanges.
    * You prefer a softer feel and do not need the same top-end stability as Rakza 7.
